[SPEAKER_03]: a bullying claim or something could be reported.

178
00:18:47,866 --> 00:18:57,931
[SPEAKER_03]: And then there's evidence, maybe cell phone evidence, texting or things that were on social media that might show otherwise.

179
00:18:57,951 --> 00:19:07,796
[SPEAKER_03]: It's not the norm, it is the exception, but it has happened within the district.

180
00:19:07,836 --> 00:19:12,938
[SPEAKER_03]: And I don't know if you could give a very kind of vague example, Principal DeLeva.

181
00:19:13,650 --> 00:19:15,432
[SPEAKER_01]: I was gonna I did have one.

182
00:19:15,472 --> 00:19:17,613
[SPEAKER_01]: The reason why I bring up is I did have one incident.

183
00:19:18,414 --> 00:19:26,140
[SPEAKER_01]: And again, as vague as I possibly can be where a family met with me, we discussed and determined that it was not bullying.

184
00:19:27,520 --> 00:19:36,228
[SPEAKER_01]: with the aggressor and then the aggressor family or the alleged aggressive family pushed back and said, well, I feel this is a false claim.

185
00:19:36,609 --> 00:19:39,611
[SPEAKER_01]: So what are you going to do to the other family kind of thing?

186
00:19:40,752 --> 00:19:42,874
[SPEAKER_01]: So that is something that did occur.

187
00:19:43,055 --> 00:19:47,198
[SPEAKER_01]: It's not something that frequently occurs, but it does occur.

188
00:19:48,683 --> 00:19:49,463
[SPEAKER_01]: once in a while.

189
00:19:49,623 --> 00:19:57,706
[SPEAKER_01]: So, I mean, that's why I kind of brought it up, because I'm trying to see, like, okay, where's the, like you said, Member Graham, like, where's the happy ground?

190
00:19:57,746 --> 00:20:06,029
[SPEAKER_01]: If everyone's going to refute, you know, if the determination is not bullying, and then you're just going to go back and say, well, well, then that's a false claim.

191
00:20:06,149 --> 00:20:10,590
[SPEAKER_01]: So what are you doing to that other person that false claimed my child as an aggressor?

192
00:20:10,610 --> 00:20:13,151
[SPEAKER_01]: I think that's something we got to look at.

193
00:20:18,770 --> 00:20:23,032
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, no, actually, thank you for that example.

194
00:20:24,652 --> 00:20:38,618
[SPEAKER_05]: I think that's really helpful for us to think through in terms of, you know, not just what does the policy say, like, you know, the law says, like, a false accusation, but I think that's different than

195
00:20:40,713 --> 00:20:44,775
[SPEAKER_05]: a report being filed that was found to be not bullying, right?

196
00:20:45,235 --> 00:21:02,842
[SPEAKER_05]: And there is a differential there, but to hear that from, if you are the aggressor's parent, you certainly would feel like this was a false claim, especially if the administration sided with your child in some way.

197
00:21:03,462 --> 00:21:08,984
[SPEAKER_05]: So I think that's really important for us to think through in terms of the policy, but also in terms of,

198
00:21:09,698 --> 00:21:17,461
[SPEAKER_05]: how we describe this process to parents and children who end up in it, right?

199
00:21:17,521 --> 00:21:30,066
[SPEAKER_05]: Like that there are consequences for false accusations, but that is not the same necessarily as a finding of not bullying, right?

200
00:21:31,707 --> 00:21:39,450
[SPEAKER_05]: So thinking about how we describe that for the users of this policy, I think is also really important.

201
00:21:43,102 --> 00:21:46,524
[SPEAKER_04]: Mayor Mrakasis Yes, thank you.

202
00:21:46,764 --> 00:21:53,429
[SPEAKER_04]: I would agree that it's important to be very clear on what we're discussing when we're talking about

203
00:21:54,900 --> 00:22:03,582
[SPEAKER_04]: false accusations and actually who determines whether something is a false accusation and what the implications are that because I think it's a slippery slope as well.

204
00:22:03,742 --> 00:22:14,843
[SPEAKER_04]: And I think that I'm not sure who's actually qualified to do that and what the implications could be, whether they would be, there might be legal or criminal ramifications as well.

205
00:22:14,903 --> 00:22:20,845
[SPEAKER_04]: So I think it's really, that's why I think it's important to have our attorney as part of this as well.

206
00:22:25,608 --> 00:22:26,309
[SPEAKER_03]: Yes.

207
00:22:27,189 --> 00:22:39,316
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, I just also wanted to say that I'm similar to DCF if I can make this scenario that when 51 a is filed.

208
00:22:42,723 --> 00:22:47,688
[SPEAKER_03]: It is ruled in for 10 days and DCF does the investigation.

209
00:22:47,708 --> 00:22:52,832
[SPEAKER_03]: And at the end of their determined investigation, they determine whether it's ruled in or ruled out.

210
00:22:53,433 --> 00:23:03,161
[SPEAKER_03]: So if a family is going to complete the bullying paperwork, we are going to look at it from the perspective of we have to rule it in.

211
00:23:04,002 --> 00:23:07,705
[SPEAKER_03]: conduct the investigation, and then at the end come to the determination.

212
00:23:07,785 --> 00:23:14,589
[SPEAKER_03]: So I don't want people to think that we don't want to go through the process.

213
00:23:14,669 --> 00:23:16,871
[SPEAKER_03]: It's better to be safe than sorry.

214
00:23:17,371 --> 00:23:23,295
[SPEAKER_03]: So complete the paperwork, submit it, and we'll conduct the investigation.

215
00:23:23,435 --> 00:23:26,017
[SPEAKER_03]: And it will either be the rule in or the rule out.

216
00:23:26,157 --> 00:23:27,418
[SPEAKER_03]: And so with DCF,

217
00:23:27,922 --> 00:23:35,025
[SPEAKER_03]: What they say to us, Department of Children and Families, is when in doubt, file, and let them make the determination.

218
00:23:35,545 --> 00:23:44,169
[SPEAKER_03]: So if a family is in doubt, they should complete the paperwork, and then let us do the investigation.

